metadata.title: Know Thyself, Captain!
metadata.content:
Know Thyself
(Setting: On a beach next to a port, in the 1700s.)
Pirate: Gold and plunder—that’s the only thrill for a real man!,
Socrates: Has it given you what you seek?,
Pirate: Aye! I had all the riches! ...Well, my crew's only loyal as the gold flows...,
Socrates: They follow greed, not you. What do you really want?,
Pirate: I could count on 'em... but only when their greed was met. I never felt truly valued.,
Socrates: True treasure is found in deep friendships—people who see your worth, not your gold.,
Pirate: I’ve never had that. Always fought for plunder, never for people.,
Pirate: I’ve sailed every sea, but what do I have? No one to share it with. Nothing that lasts.,
Pirate: Aye… I already got to know the seven seas. I guess it’s time to get to know myself.,
Socrates: Fair winds, captain. You’ve set a wiser course.

metadata.title: Question Everything, Galileo!
metadata.content:
Title: "Socrates and Galileo: Question Everything"

Characters: Templar Knight, Galileo, Socrates 

 Panel 1: Wide shot of a quiet garden at dusk. Socrates and Galileo walk side by side. Galileo holds a telescope, gazing at the stars. Galileo: The heavens… They’ve always said the Earth is the center of it all.

Panel 2: Socrates: Have you seen it with your own eyes?

Panel 3: Close-up of Galileo, looking troubled. Galileo: No, but the Church says it’s so. It’s been believed for centuries.

Panel 4: Socrates stops, his expression serious: Should we accept it simply because it’s always been said? Or should we seek the truth ourselves?

Panel 5: Flashback of Galileo looking through his telescope, discovering moons around Jupiter. A look of realization dawns on his face. Galileo (voiceover): I saw moons orbiting Jupiter… It made no sense if everything revolved around Earth.

Panel 6: Galileo looks back at Socrates, internally seeing memories of a templar knight killing revolutionists, uncertainty in his eyes: But challenging the Church... The risk is great.

Panel 7: Socrates: Is a life without questioning worth living? You risk more by accepting what might be false.

Panel 8: Close-up of Galileo’s face, reflecting Socrates’ words. He clutches the telescope, his grip tightening. Galileo: If we stop questioning, we stop seeking truth.

Panel 9: Socrates smiles, the stars reflected in his eyes. Socrates: And truth, my friend, is the greatest discovery of all.

Panel 10: Galileo lifts his telescope toward the sky, his resolve clear. Galileo: Then I’ll keep searching. The heavens have more to reveal.

Panel 11: Socrates walks off into the night. Socrates: Question everything, Galileo. That’s the only path to wisdom.

metadata.title: Admit Your Ignorance, Or Become Guilty Of Destruction
metadata.content:
Admit Ignorance

1
 Characters: Soldier, Cuban Police, Castro 

 Fidel Castro: I know exactly what everybody needs, better than the people themselves. (laughing arrogantly)

2
Fidel Castro: My soldiers force my controlling and unrealistic policies onto all the workers. (Image of a soldier with a rifle on a farm)

3
Fidel Castro: Anybody who reports back bad numbers must be wrong and executed. (scared bureaucrat)

4
Fidel Castro: People are starving to death? Not my fault. (corpses on the street and the fields)

5
Fidel Castro: I killed their previous oppressor, they should be grateful. (police beating down protestors)

6
Socrates confronting Castro: You know NOTHING! You are just another scumbag turned mass murderer, by failing to admit your ignorance.

metadata.title: Weak Men Create Hard Times
metadata.content:
Father Figures and Obligation to Physical Discipline

Socrates Voiceover on all panels:

1
2022 USA
Most people are addicted to sugar.
(obese family in candyshop)

2
Youngsters race or have deadly gangfights.
(gangsters with cars)

3
Most elders assume it's normal to be crippled.
(lonely crippled elder in wheelchair)

4
Only boys in old bodies around here.
(showing immature man)

5
Seems like real fathers are missing, to teach them...
(a single mother alone with her daughter)

6
...that...
(Socrates in a gym, 79 years old, but still super fit with a sixpack and big arms)

7
“No one has the right to be an amateur in the matter of physical training. It is a shame to grow old without seeing the beauty and strength of which the body is capable” - Socrates

metadata.title: No Knowledge, No Virtue
metadata.content:
“Virtue is Knowledge”

Panel 1:
(Setting: Nero’s lavish palace, with Socrates standing calmly, and Nero lounging arrogantly on a throne. The palace is filled with excess, gold, and decadent decorations.)

Nero:
"I am the most powerful man in Rome. I can do whatever I wish."

Panel 2:
(Socrates raises an eyebrow, standing humbly, unphased by the wealth around him.)

Socrates:
"Power without wisdom is a dangerous thing, Nero."

Panel 3:
(Nero waves dismissively, his face showing irritation.)

Nero:
"What do I need wisdom for? I know how to enjoy life, how to command, and how to conquer."

Panel 4:
(Socrates points to the excess around them—the luxuries, feasts, and sycophants—highlighting Nero’s indulgence.)

Socrates:
"Do you know what is truly good? Or do you just know how to satisfy your desires?"

Panel 5:
(Nero scoffs, looking out at Rome through a window, the city below beginning to burn—hinting at the Great Fire of Rome.)

Nero:
"I am Rome. I define what is good."

Panel 6:
(Socrates, calm but firm, looks Nero in the eyes, a faint fire reflected in the background.)

Socrates:
"If you truly knew what was good, you would not be destroying it."

metadata.title: Truth Is Victory, The Only Victory
metadata.content:
Truth Over Victory

Panel 1
Scene: 3rd Century BCE Emperor Ashoka stands on the battlefield, staring at the ruins left behind. Socrates approaches, standing beside him, both watching the aftermath in silence.

Socrates: "A heavy cost for victory, isn’t it?"

Panel 2
Ashoka looks deeply troubled, his eyes fixed on the suffering of the people—civilians and soldiers alike. In the background, homes are destroyed and families mourn.

Ashoka: "I won the war, but all I see is pain. Was this the only way?"

Panel 3
Socrates, thoughtful but not judgmental, watches the scene with him. His expression is calm, contemplative.

Socrates: "What did you seek, Ashoka? Victory? Or truth?"

Panel 4
Ashoka stands before a statue of the Buddha in a peaceful temple, his royal armor replaced by simpler robes. Monks meditate around him, the atmosphere serene.

Ashoka: "The Buddha spoke of peace, compassion, and wisdom. I ignored his teachings… but now, I see truth in them."

Panel 5
Ashoka (meditating in a garden): From now on, hold me accountable to Ahimsa: Non-violence.

Panel 6
Socrates: This, Ashoka, is true victory.

metadata.title: Ghandi The Stoic: Focus On What You Can Control
metadata.content:
Gandhi the Stoic: Focus on what you can control

Mahatma Gandhi in the 1940s, in South Africa, before starting his final big movement.

1
Gandhi: The oppression is overwhelming, I feel powerless.

2
Socrates: I heard you have a good foundation of communication skills. What is the best solution you can think of?

3
Gandhi: We would have to be enough people, but it is impossible to unite.

4
Socrates: Is that so? Isn't there something in your control that you could focus on?

5
Gandhi, looking up: Sometimes I inspire others by being principled. I could double down on that, but it can seem radical and offputting.

6
Gandhi, standing filled with a spark of hope: Wait... if I master the message of non-violence, maybe people won't be repelled. It is worth a try!

metadata.title: Socratic Warning Before The Challenger Disaster
metadata.content:
Socratic Warning Before the Challenger

Panel 1:
Setting: NASA control room, just before launch. Socrates stands beside the scientist, who reviews data. Engineers are murmuring concerns.

Scientist:
“Some engineers worry about the O-rings. But we can’t delay again. Everyone says it's fine.”

Panel 2:
Close-up of Socrates, pointing at the data.

Socrates:
“Is the truth decided by what everyone else says, or by the facts before you?”

Panel 3:
The scientist frowns, glancing between the data and the window showing the shuttle ready for launch.

Scientist:
“We’ve delayed too much. If we stop now, we will look bad.”

Panel 4:
Socrates places a hand on the scientist’s shoulder, eyes serious.

Socrates:
“Truth doesn’t change. What’s worse—delay or disaster?”

Panel 5:
The scientist looks unsure, biting his lip as the countdown begins.

Scientist:
“The world is watching. What if it works?”

Panel 6:
Close-up of Socrates, giving a solemn warning.

Socrates:
“Hope doesn’t change reality. Trust truth, not opinions, if you value life.”
